				<position place="head" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Natura, Ars, Exercitatio, quanta potest extendi
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						vlla vi.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Nature, art, exercise: how much it can be extended with force. 
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						Bona animi, corporis,
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						) fortuna[e], quovis
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						modo
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						multiplicanda. Singula corporis membra
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						decenti&ugrave;s componenda, qu&agrave;m alioru[m]:
						omnesq[ue] totius hominis ) partes ) ad exquisitiorem perfectionem
						) redigenda[e],
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						) qu&agrave;m vllus alter pra[e]sentium
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						pra[e] se fert. Pra[e]sertim vultus,
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position place="tail" book_orientation="0">
					<marginalia_text>
						) vox, gestus, tota actio[que]
						quicquid deniq[ue] commendat virum.
						Sed quasi inaffectat&egrave;: et semper omniu[m] facillim&egrave;.
					</marginalia_text>
					<emphasis method="chalk" type="straight"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The good things of the soul, body, and fortune, must be multiplied in whatever manner.
				The singular members of the body must be composed more appropriately than those of others,
				and all the parts of the complete man must be brought to a perfection more exquisite than any other present man.
				particularly the face, voice, gesture, and in short, whatever complete action that distinguishes the man. 
				But it must always be as if effortless and the easiest thing in the world.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
